404 "N.B.  There are various questions and properties about prime numb
ers which are of interest and study.  For example, it is known that th
ere are infinitely many primes.  There is only one even prime. (Why?) \+
 The distribution of the odd primes is not fully understood.  If two c
onsecutive odd numbers are both prime (e.g., (5,7) ; (17,19), (101,103
)), then such a pair of consecutive odd primes is called a " }{TEXT 
282 19 "pair of twin primes" }{TEXT -1 174 ".  It is not known whether
 or not there are infinitely many such pairs of twin primes.  It is kn
own that there can be arbitrarily large gaps between consecutive prime
s.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
372 "5.  Relatively Prime Numbers.  Two positive integers are said to \+
be relatively prime if the only positive integer which (evenly) divide
s both of them is 1.  Examples of  (pairs of) relatively prime integer
s are:  74, 51;   13, 120;   344280, 267317.  If two integers are rela
tively prime, then the greatest common divisor of the two integers mus
t be 1.  The maple command " }{TEXT 278 3 "gcd" }{TEXT -1 296 " can be
 used to determine whether greatest common divisor of two integers is \+
1, i.e., whether the two integers are relatively prime.  Show that eac
h of the above mentioned pairs of integers are relatively prime.  Find
 three other pairs of relatively prime integers with the following con
straints:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 72 "(a) neither integer is itsel
f prime; (b) each integer is more than 1000." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
